<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,646]" box="[151,390,151,177]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading box="[151,390,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="5">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[151,390,151,177]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="yunganus">
<emphasis box="[151,390,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Hylaeamys yunganus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Karyotype: 2n = 58 and FN = 62. Autosomal complement: three small metacentric pairs, and 25 acrocentric pairs large to small decreasing in size. Sex chromosomes: X, a large acrocentric; Y, a small acrocentric (
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref67114" refString="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L. (1976) Karyotypic variation in Oryzomyine rodents (Cricetinae) with comments on chromosomal evolution in the Neotropical Cricetine complex. Occasional papers of the Museum of Zoology, 49, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1976">Gardner &amp; Patton 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pp. 6, 
<figureCitation box="[365,451,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1191,1215]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,281,1162]" captionTargetId="figure-69@7.[151,1436,273,1168]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of diploid and fundamental number of karyotyped specimens of genus Cerradomys. (□) C. akroai; (■) C. goytaca; (ê) C. langguthi; (r) C. maracajuensis; (▲) C. marinhus; (○) C. scotti; (☆) C. subflavus; (l) C. vivoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423619/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Patton, J. L. &amp; Silva, M. N. &amp; Malcolm, J. R." box="[462,660,259,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref71077" refString="Patton, J. L., Silva, M. N. &amp; Malcolm, J. R. (2000) Mammals of the Rio Jurua and the evolutionary and ecological diversification of Amazonia. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 244, 1 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 244 % 3 C 0001: MOTRJA % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">
Patton 
<emphasis box="[539,587,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M." box="[669,977,259,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="295 - 304" refId="ref74775" refString="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M. (2000) Comparative chromosome banding analysis of three South American species of rice rats of the genus Oryzomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Chromosome Research, 8, 295 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1009223210737" type="journal article" year="2000">Volobouev &amp; Aniskin 2000</bibRefCitation>
). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes and on the X chromosome. G-banding was also performed (
<bibRefCitation author="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M." box="[428,741,331,357]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="295 - 304" refId="ref74775" refString="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M. (2000) Comparative chromosome banding analysis of three South American species of rice rats of the genus Oryzomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Chromosome Research, 8, 295 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1009223210737" type="journal article" year="2000">Volobouev &amp; Aniskin 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
A different karyotype was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L." box="[625,904,367,394]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref67114" refString="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L. (1976) Karyotypic variation in Oryzomyine rodents (Cricetinae) with comments on chromosomal evolution in the Neotropical Cricetine complex. Occasional papers of the Museum of Zoology, 49, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1976">Gardner &amp; Patton (1976)</bibRefCitation>
, with 2n = 60 and FN = 66, the karyotype of this form was nearly identical to that one mentioned before except for the presence of a small metacentric pair. Another karyotype with 2n = 60 and NF = 64 was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andrades-Miranda, J. &amp; Zanchin, N. I. T. &amp; Oliveira, L. F. B. &amp; Langguth, A. R. &amp; Mattevi, M. S." box="[759,1120,439,465]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="461 - 472" refId="ref63611" refString="Andrades-Miranda, J., Zanchin, N. I. T., Oliveira, L. F. B., Langguth, A. R. &amp; Mattevi, M. S. (2000) Cytogenetic studies in nine taxa of the genus Oryzomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae) from Brazil. Mammalia, 65 (4), 461 - 472. https: // doi. org / 10.1515 / mamm. 2001.65.4.461" type="journal article" year="2000">
Andrades-Miranda 
<emphasis box="[978,1027,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. (2000)
</bibRefCitation>
. This karyotype was similar to the one reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L." box="[403,683,475,502]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref67114" refString="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L. (1976) Karyotypic variation in Oryzomyine rodents (Cricetinae) with comments on chromosomal evolution in the Neotropical Cricetine complex. Occasional papers of the Museum of Zoology, 49, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1976">Gardner &amp; Patton (1976)</bibRefCitation>
(2n = 60, FN = 66), the difference was due to one more acrocentric pair and one less small biarmed pair, resulting in a FN = 64. Samples from 
<collectingCountry box="[1011,1118,511,537]" name="Suriname" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Suriname</collectingCountry>
presented a diploid number from 52 to 59 and fundamental number from 64 to 67 (
<bibRefCitation author="Koop, B. F. &amp; Baker, R. J. &amp; Genoways, H. H." box="[765,958,547,573]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="131 - 135" refId="ref68467" refString="Koop, B. F., Baker, R. J. &amp; Genoways, H. H. (1983) Numerous chromosomal polymorphisms in a natural population of rice rats (Oryzomys, Cricetidae). Cytogenetics and Cell Genetics, 35, 131 - 135. https: // doi. org / 10.1159 / 000131854" type="journal article" year="1983">
Koop 
<emphasis box="[836,885,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. 1983
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kerridge, D. C. &amp; Baker, R. J." box="[970,1239,547,573]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="5 - 7" refId="ref68301" refString="Kerridge, D. C. &amp; Baker, R. J. (1990) Genetic variation and origin of the most chromosomally polymorphic natural mammalian population. Cytogenetics and Cell Genetics, 53, 5 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.1159 / 000132884" type="journal article" year="1990">Kerridge &amp; Baker 1990</bibRefCitation>
). The variation in diploid and fundamental number of samples from 
<collectingCountry box="[727,834,583,609]" name="Suriname" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Suriname</collectingCountry>
occurs sympatrically, whereas the others karyotypes reported for the genus represent different populations (
<tableCitation box="[762,849,618,645]" captionStart="TABLE 5" captionStartId="25.[151,239,527,553]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="TABLE 5. Karyotype data of genus Hylaeamys. Species, diploid (2n) and fundamental (FN) numbers, collection localities, geographic coordinates and reference." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Table 5</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[861,928,619,646]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[160,1430,712,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-177@23.[151,1436,705,1602]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of diploid and fundamental number of karyotyped specimens of genus Hylaeamys. (□) H. megacephalus; (■) H. oniscus; (○) H. perenensis; (l) H. seuanezi; (ê) H. yunganus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423629" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423629/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
